🩷KCL Dance Soc’s End of Year Show 2024🩷

We are so excited to finally announce our end of year show dancer auditions! We have such an incredible line up of talented choreographers creating the pieces for our show this year. 

The EOYS will be on March 20th, 21st and 22nd 2024, at Greenwood theatre. Dancer auditions begin on the 22nd of January and end on the 26th. Don’t be afraid to join and try something new! 

All in-person auditions will take place during the relevant piece/s rehearsal time slot which can be found in the post. The only audition that will be held at a different time slot is Mel and Lydia’s Lyrical, which will take place on Wednesday 24th from 21:00-22:00 in ARF (Strand). If you cannot make a rehearsal slot please contact the choreographer below to ask about a virtual audition. There is no need to sign up; just bring water and comfy clothes to dance in. The choreographer will teach you a section of choreography and then will contact you if you are successful. Do not worry about preparing anything in advance! Please come 5-10 minutes before the audition so a committee member can note down your contact information. 

We are really excited to see you all at auditions! Please reach out if you have any questions! Our choreographers are tagged below if you have any piece-specific questions. 

Our show name and colour will be released soon so stay tuned for this 😉👀

How will the three worlds—represented by the United States and Europe, China and Russia, and the grouping of non-western developing nations—shape struggles over rules and institutions for the coming decades ahead? More importantly, will the support and cooperation of the Global South tilt the balance towards the West’s or the East’s favor? Join the Oxford International Relations Society and Professor John Ikenberry to discuss the West, East and South and the competition to shape global order on Feb 8th from 6pm to 7pm.

🥺❤️President
Responsibilities
Leading the 16-person committee and holding weekly committee meetings 
Oversee all Dance Soc activities from classes to shows to socials to comps
Ensuring that your committee are balancing their workload well with their uni work, and are prepared for their role - this includes the show production teams they’re in and also general and specific dance soc duties! 
Liaising with the Students Union and ArtsUCL on how to make Dance Soc even better, dealing with complaints, refunds and sometimes even filling out forms
Communicating with the society’s members regarding elections, special things going on in the society 
Producing ‘Triple Bill’, our annual charity show 

Gemma’s comments
I loved being President of Dance Society this year. I love my committee because everyone is giving their all to help Dance Society thrive and become even better! Being President isn’t for everyone. You need to have a love for Dance Soc and all that it brings. This role is chaotic, but so fulfilling and fun that you’ll grow to love it!!! 

Dance Society is one of the biggest societies at UCL, which means the workload is big, but I promise it is manageable!! It is by far one of the most rewarding things I’ve had the chance to be as you work closely with every single person on committee, feel proud of them and the activities, shows we are able to produce. 

On top of leading the society, you’ll also be the producer for our annual charity show Triple Bill. this year was a super success as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of TB!!! , this is one of the most enjoyable things I’ve done.

I believe the qualities you’d need are: problem solving, time management, multi-tasking, responsibility, being assertive, fair and passionate for Dance Soc. You will need to look at an event, and be able to foresee any possible problems and plan ahead of time to avoid issues, working with your team of 15 and getting things done. Most importantly, you should be dedicated to dance soc and genuinely care about the members and events - it makes the hours of unpaid work worth it <33 

If you’re thinking of running for pres, message me any questions and good luck!! @gems_jewel

🕺🏻🍬Social Secretary 
Responsibilities
Organise a wide range of inclusive socials for the society
Contact local bars and pubs for post show socials 
Plan the dance soc summer ball; you have a prod team to help!
Help to produce one of our many shows 

Tia’s comments:
Social secretary primarily involves the organisation of the events throughout the year - from movies, to quiz nights and the post show socials. Your biggest task is the planning of the summer ball at the end of the year!

This is a great role for somebody who is outgoing and friendly. The socials help to build a bigger sense of community, so make sure to offer a broad variety to include EVERYONE! Try and find things that fit in well with the rest of the dance soc calendar, it is a busy one! Beyond being a friendly face, you need some top notch organisation skills and a willingness to communicate on the phone with venue owners ;) 

The best part of this role for me has been connecting with a wide range of people in our dance community as well as the creative freedom that comes with it.

All in all, this role has been incredibly rewarding and I am so grateful for the wonderful peeps on my socials prod team and everybody who I have met along the way, new and old. There is also a huge amount of creative freedom that comes alongside being social sec so make the most of it!

Tolgar Sirvanci is a Managing Director in PGIM Private Capital’s London Corporate Finance office. He oversees private placement and mezzanine activity in the UK managing a US$11.8 billion portfolio (as of 30.9.23) of senior debt, mezzanine debt and private equity investments. Prior to this role, Tolgar led a team responsible for marketing, originating, and managing private placement and mezzanine investments in London, Scandinavia, and Turkey. Tolgar joined Pricoa in 2002 as an Analyst in the Chicago office and re-located to London in 2006. 

Tolgar received a BBA and a BSE from the University of Wisconsin at Madison. He holds the Chartered Financial Analyst® designation.

Introducing our publicity, mentoring, and conference teams, and our ambassador coordinator.

💡MEET THE SPEAKERS #1: Dr Clare Hickman

Dr Clare Hickman is an environmental and medical historian focusing on post 1750 Britain, based at Newcastle University. Her recent Wellcome Fellowship, The Garden as a Laboratory, merged the history of medicine, health and science, with that of the landscape and environment. The research from this has just been published as a monograph, The Doctor’s Garden: Medicine, Science and Horticulture in Late Georgian Britain by Yale University Press. Other areas of expertise include the design and use of nineteenth and twentieth-century English hospital and asylum gardens, cold bathing as a healthy activity in the eighteenth-century landscape garden and the role of medical practitioners in the Victorian parks movement. Her research crosses the disciplinary boundaries of medical history, landscape history and history of science.

To register for the conference (9 March), fill in the form at the link in our bio by 5 March!

RECONNECT OPEN CALL 🌜🌛
 
We invite the students from the Courtauld Institute of Art, King’s College, UCL, Goldsmiths and the Slade School of Fine Art to join us in the reflection on reconnect. A word that stands for another connection, coming back to something that was lost. We can think about it in many different aspects. As a reconnection with people (friends, family), lost habits, places or art (films, books, paintings). As students we can highlight the need of reconnection with our universities and the rest of the student body which was made unavailable to us in the current situation. We can wonder, why the initial contact has been lost or what is motivating the will for return. Why sometimes it is so important for us to reconnect? What feelings do we associate with the thing that we lost?
 
We invite everyone to submit their artworks on the theme of reconnect. They can have a form of visual art: painting, photography, drawing, sculpture, collage as well as literary texts. They will be showcased in an exhibition organized on the occasion of the 25th issue of the Courtauldian, a student-run arts and culture publication society at the Courtauld Institute of Art that focuses on support, treasure and embrace of artistic and literary talent. This event is a collaboration with the King’s College Art Society and students coming from Art History departments of UCL, Goldsmiths and the Slade School of Fine Arts.
 
The committee will select a number of participants who will receive a feature on the Courtauldian’s website as artist of the month, as well as a possibility to design a two-page spread in the next issue.
 
We hope this event will be a beginning of reconnection between the different artistic universities and schools all around London.
 
If you would like to contribute all you need is send your artwork to reconnect.submissions@gmail.com
By 27th of March.
The artworks will be showcased through an online exhibition. If the current restrictions in the UK change, they will also be presented at an in-person event. 

@thecourtauldian @sladeschool @goldsmithsart @courtauld_su @uclhoas @kclartsoc @goldsmithssu

✈ Pilot profile - Neil Swinton
This week we meet the big cheese 🧀 Chief Flying Instructor Neil.

🛫 What got you into gliding? "I flew toy gliders in my youth (still do really), and had a few glider flights at Booker with my school friend's father, but even then it was obvious I couldn't afford that sort of expenditure. Then a week away a few years later flying Blaniks and T21's at a Sutton Bank holiday course. Then onto Oxford to learn on the K13's, Ka8 and a sweet club Ka6 CR."

❤ Favourite gliding memory: "Many spring to mind, like avoiding my first landout somewhere near Corby by blundering into a stubble fire which took me from 700' to 7000', luckily without setting the Ka6 on fire.
Also being on the team that replaced the failed diesel engine on the winch with a 'new' replacement overnight. Led by Andrew Butterfield, we started around 4pm on Saturday, and it was finished and ready for use on the Sunday morning. As is often the way, people on Sunday just carried on as normal with no idea of what had occurred.
The best thing in the past few years have the club trips away with a K21 to Aston down, Cambridge, Sutton Bank, and Long Mynd. We are hopefully doing Camphill next spring, if anyone wants to join us!"

⭐ Fun fact: Neil does indeed like cheese 🧀 "my favourite is mascarpone".

⬆ Next gliding goal? "Ambitions, very few, but to continue enjoying gliding."

📸: 1) Neil enjoying the sundeck of his DG (registration G-DEMU, apparently flies better than an actual emu), 2) part of Neil's CFI role is playing the role of "worst student ever" when training instructors, 3) Neil after taking Cotswold GC's K18 for a spin!

Happy New Year! 

Gujarati new year, also known as Bestu Varas, occurs after Diwali. On this year, people celebrate with their family, visit loved ones, sit in pooja and close last years’ “chopda” (accounting book) to open the new chopda which was worshipped on Diwali, signifying the start to a new year and to gain the blessings of god for a successful financial year. 

We wish you and your families a prosperous, healthy and happy year ahead 💛

The LSESU Moroccan Society is honoured to host HE Mr Abdellatif Miraoui, Moroccan Minister of Higher Education, Scientific Research and Innovation. The event will take place Thursday 8th December at 15.30 GMT 

The topic of discussion is Morocco's aims and objectives as part of the ministry's new plan for higher education and ways in which British and Moroccan universities interact and collaborate. 

HE Mr Abdellatif Miraoui was appointed minister in September 2021 after having served as president of Cadi-Ayyad University from 2011-2019. He also currently serves as the honorary president of the Association of Francophone Universities. 

We are also delighted to have Dr Marina Cino Pagliarello chair this discussion. Dr Cino Pagliarello is a Visiting Fellow at the European Institute at LSE and a Research Associate at LSE Consulting. Her area of expertise extensively covers higher education and social policy. 

This event is open to ALL students from British universities. To access the event, the sign-up form MUST be filled out.

Ever wondered what working for a non-profit feels like? Join us next Thursday for an event jointly hosted with the Ecosoc for a conversation with Anna Barker.
We will discuss what it is like to work in a charity, the famous Fairtrade foundation! Surely you've already seen their logo on the bananas you buy. 

Fairtrade is an independent non-profit organisation that licenses the use of the Fairtrade Mark on products in the UK in accordance with specific standards such as better wages and living conditions for product suppliers. 

Moreso than discussing Fairtrade, we will be able to discuss Anna's career path, as she has been working on responsible sourcing, ethical trade and sustainable supply chains across multiple commodities for over 6 years. 

Join us on Thursday at 5 pm NAB 2.14 for what promises to be a fascinating discussion! 📍 

We are exciting to see you there! 🌵

Jotello Festiri Soga was the UK’s first black veterinarian. He graduated from Dick Veterinary School in Edinburgh in 1886. Dr. Soga played an enormous role in the eradication of Rinderpest, an extremely deadly disease that resulted in the deaths of millions of cattle. Because of his work, eventually a vaccine was created to protect cattle against Rinderpest, and the disease has since been eradicated from the planet. Learn more about him by clicking the link in our story. 

#blackhistorymonth #bhm #veterinarian #diversity #ukvet #inclusivity

Ever wonder about the connection between philosophy and film studies? Join us this Monday as Professor Andrew Klevan teaches us about the intersection of these fields! Professor Klevan is a Professor of Film Aesthetics as part of the University of Oxford Faculty of English. He focuses on interests like film criticism, aesthetics, philosophy of criticism, analysis of film style and form, and the methodology and pedagogy of film study.

In this talk, Professor Klevan will introduce some of the various ways film studies has intersected with philosophy in the fields known as Film-Philosophy and Film Aesthetics. The talk will also include a Q&A component, so please come with any questions you have!

The Feast of the Holy Face was established by Pope Pius XII upon Shrove Tuesday (the day before Ash Wednesday, the start of Lent).

Illumina, Domine, vultum tuum super nos. 

“I firmly wish that My face reflecting the intimate pains of my soul, the suffering and love of my heart, be more honoured! Whoever gazes upon me already consoles me.”(Our Lord Jesus to Sister Maria Pierina)

The Shroud of Turin is a centuries old linen cloth that bears the image of a crucified man. A man that millions believe to be Jesus of Nazareth. This miraculous object, said to be the burial cloth of Christ, came to light in Turin the Middle Ages where it is now kept, although rarely shown, because of its fragility. It has been the subject of great devotion and also of intense scientific study. The image, showing the marks of Christ’s crucifixion, does not appear to have been been painted, but has been miraculously imprinted into the cloth.

Welcome to our PuckPuck/AeroPress cold brew method. I wrote the steps as alt text for those who aren’t able to view the photos. We are lucky enough to have been sponsored by AeroPress for events, and we are very excited to get them in to use :). 

I will write the full instructions here too:

1. Grind 38g of coffee beans into medium ground coffee, darker roasts might require a more course grind size to prevent over extraction. This is as less dense dark roasted beans are easier to extract than dense light roasted ones.

2. Insert a filter into the AeroPress as normal, then place your AeroPress over a carafe and pour in your ground coffee.

3. Place the puck puck water screen on the top of the ground coffee, making sure it’s as level as it can be - this helps to prevent channelling.

4. Attach PuckPuck and reservoir to the AeroPress.

5. Fill with water up to 500ml, then twist the collar until you achieve a steady drip rate of 50-60 drops per minute. (PuckPuck has a handy app to help with this.)

6. Wait, drink, enjoy. Your cold brew should be ready within a few hours.

We stand in solidarity with the oppressed people of Indian Occupied Kashmir and their right to self-determination.

We support the right for all societies at the LSE to carry out events regarding Kashmiri Occupation.

The conversation about Kashmir only starts here.

Continue to encourage societies throughout the LSE to carry out events regarding the heinous human rights abuses that have been taking place in Kashmir since its occupation.

🎉 Some MT23 Highlights 🎉

1) Hosting Dame Melinda Simmons, British Ambassador to Ukraine 2019-2023

2) Our first NATO lecture, with Dr Amy Ertan discussing NATO's prepardedness in the realm of cyber defence. See more of the NATO Project here @natoxdiplo!

3) A guest lecture delivered by Paul Docherty, drawing on his experience with the British Council to discuss Soft Power. 

4) Our fourth and final NATO lecture, with Renata Zaleska discussing the NATO Partners arrangement.

5) A panel discussion with early and mid-career diplomats, studying here in Oxford, giving insight into their greatest challenges and advice for other aspiring diplomats. Special thanks to contributors Yuliia Shaipova, Muqeet Shah, Raúl Taveras, Nieves Cancela, and Suvanga Parajuli! 

6) Our online panel on economic diplomacy in a multipolar world, with Dr Alex Vines of Chatham House, Dr Emmanuel Ikechukwu of the Organisation of African Academic Doctors, and Hannah Grupp of the World Bank, and chaired by Oxford's Nicolas Lippolis. 

7) The address by the Finnish Ambassador to the UK, H.E. Jukka Siukosaari, commencing the NATOxDiplo competition's Grand Final. 

8) In conversation with John Taylor, former diplomat and intelligence expert, speaking on his experience in the Soviet Union and Russia. 

9) The virtual address from the Armenian Ambassador to the UK, H.E. Varuzhan Nersesyan. 

This is only a small number of the 31 events we hosted this term, but thank you to all our speakers and guests, and to all the Society members who attended! We hope to see you all again next term!

Our International Festival Event - The Chinese Traditional Crosstalk Workshop 'Comedy On Campus' is coming! （相声进校园活动来啦！！）🏮🐼

🕕Date&Time: 20th Feb, 18:00-20:00

👅We recommend you have a good acquaintance of mandarin to attend this workshop!
👉Check out the programme in our poster!
🙋Sign up by scanning the QR Code in the poster!

🐉The London Crosstalk Club (伦敦相声大会), in collaboration with UCL CSSA @mist_dramastudio will be hosting a workshop titled 'Comedy on Campus' on the 20th of February, 10 days after the commencement of the Year of Loong.
@uclcssa_official

🙋Many people who have grown up in contemporary Chinese culture share a particular experience of watching traditional crosstalk during the Chinese New Year. Crosstalk, also known as Xiangsheng, has a special place in entertainment during the Spring Festival, it can be seen at the Chinese New Year Gala, presented to television audiences, or at the temple fairs, Miaohui, in front of live audiences. We are thrilled to organise this workshop in London, at UCL, with the hope of adding a little bit of laughter to the participants' experience of Chinese New Year.

👫We are delighted to announce that we will be inviting crosstalk actors and actresses with a wealth of experience in both China and overseas to perform, as well as discuss the interaction between a form of traditional comedy from the nineteenth century and the contemporary environment, especially in an overseas setting. Participants will also be invited to experience learning crosstalk and practicing Chinese calligraphy with the hosts.

Everyone is welcome! However, given that the main part of the workshop, the performance and discussion about crosstalk, will be in mandarin, and other parts of the event will include interactive experiences in Chinese language, fluency in Mandarin is desirable for non-native Chinese speakers to come along.

@uclcssa_artroupe @uclchinesedancecrew @mandarin.edu.soc @mist_dramastudio @studentsunionucl @uclculture

Want to know more about behavioural data science? Join us in-person on Monday 27th for Prof Pogrebna’s presentation: “Advancing Behavioral Change through Data Science: Insights and Applications”

This presentation will delve into the realm of behavioral data science, a novel field at the intersection of behavioral science, economics, psychology, data science, and computer science. It focuses on three key aspects of post-AI revolution behavior: 

(i) human behavior, emphasizing understanding and influencing individual and group decision-making; 
(ii) algorithmic behavior, addressing the identification and mitigation of biases in AI and understanding human-algorithm interactions;
(iii) systems behavior, aimed at designing efficient systems for optimal team and organizational performance. 

The talk will introduce attendees to the essentials of behavioral data science and its relevance to areas such as healthcare, public policy, education, and more. Through real-world case studies, the presentation will showcase how behavioral data science transforms traditional approaches, driving significant advancements in various sectors, particularly in fostering impactful behavioral change. The focus will be on how these innovations lead to more effective strategies and interventions for both individuals and organizations.

Last week we welcomed Tom Holmes, founder and CEO of Toms Trunks to talk to us about his clothing brand and the battle to keep sustainability a priority during rapid business growth. Tom highlighted the challenges of making clothes production and supply sustainable, but has shown incredible commitment to reducing the carbon footprint of his entire business, from factory to shipping to marketing methods. Tom has introduced a number of innovative practises to ameliorate the footprint of the fashion industry, focusing on reducing waste, slowing fashion through creating lifetime products and using renewable energy for factories. Tom was steadfast in the belief that sustainability has to start at their level, and is determined to change the narrative that sustainability equals higher cost.

Hi everyone, we are Oxford Student Faith Action

Who are we?
We are a coalition of organisations fighting for increased clarity and inclusion for LGBTQ+ Christians in Oxford. We represent multiple LGBTQ+ organisations in Oxford, as well as Churches.

What are we doing?
Today we will be publishing our first faith report called ‘Attitudes to Queer Christians in Oxford Churches’. This report ranks churches in Oxford on how friendly they are to LGBTQ+ people from a score of 1 to 5. Our goal was to assemble evidence so that LGBTQ+ people can make informed decisions about where they go to church, and protect them from harm. 

The full report is listed in our bio, and at the QR code.

Dr. Abigail Branford is a dedicated scholar whose research explores the intricate dynamics of post-conflict education, postcolonial knowledge production, and issues of gender and gender-based violence in various contexts. With a background in Transitional Justice and an MPhil in Education, Globalisation, and Development from the University of Cambridge, Abigail delved into the complex interplay of education and historical legacies, particularly regarding the understanding of the British Empire in secondary schools in England.

This exploration extended to examining educational institutions’ roles in shaping postcolonial knowledge. She also brings a wealth of experience from previous work on teaching apartheid histories in South Africa and the politics of academic publishing in West African universities. With a commitment to research and intervention against intimate partner violence, Abigail Branford continues to make valuable contributions to academia. Currently, Abigail Branford serves as a lecturer in African Studies at the University of Oxford, where she also completed her doctorate at the prestigious Department of Education.

Join the Advance Africa Conference to learn more about Abigail's career trajectory and to network with other leading career professionals across Africa.

Well, well, well….

First of all, let’s get off on the right foot. Yes, I am as surprised as you are to be reading this caption. But we actually ran a social. The annuls of LSE history will quake with what was a momentous occasion.

Let’s lay down some ground rules… 

1) DONT leave the meet with about 1 hour to go, especially without messaging us. We won’t bite. And we get it, we haven’t shown our faces since Freshers, but still, poor form. 

2) Lateness IS rudeness. Anakin Big Bowler learned that lesson. It starts at 4, not 4.17. In the future it will be punished 

Annnyway, what a day. They spoke of this social as a matter of fiction but boy, did we prove them wrong. Sec was on the beers since 9am to make sure he was on form for what was a momentous occasion.

Barman recognised me from last time and knew there were no straws required. Offered me a pint of their ‘house blend’. Interesting concoction. In hind sight it was probably fine-able but since they were offering free bowling I decided to allow it 

Bowling was underway, and there was no sign of the ‘Big Bowler’. After all that chat,aswell. You’ll learn for next time son. And there will be a next time, trust me on that. 

The old adage held true. Some things never change, as the sec pulled out yet another victory. He had to do it the hard way though, as Zaheen fought right till the end. But the sec, clutch as ever, turned up when it mattered most, and raised the victory in front of the people. Sal and Ben also performed well

What a day. One of those that people think would never live up to the hype. But it did. We will return. The train does not stop once it gets rolling. We are coming for the SU

Until next time

🎉WOMEN’S BUCS LEAGUE MEET 1🎉

With an amazing performance from last season, we headed into this season with high hopes. We may have lost some amazing players from last year, but this didn’t rattle our team. They took the challenge head on and hit a home run sky high!! ☄️

We started of against the formidable Winchester 1s, and what a game it was. It was a rollercoaster ride with both sides having a claw in the game. It was literally a tug of war but our MVP Yuna’s powerful shots gave us the final pull to help us gain a victory against them (11-9). 

One often meets their destiny, on the road they take to avoid it. Portsmouth 1s was our next challenge and we faced our destiny head on. It was a path we had to cross, but we marched through with no fears in our eyes. With a massive team performance, we succeeded a win (15-5) and our battle was legendary!!

Can’t wait for the next league meet. I hope this momentum will continue and for many more battles ahead!!!

🍕 On Tuesday, February 13 we will begin the day with a Pizza and Bake sale from 11am with 9 other LSESU societies and clubs! 80% of our proceeds will go to Medical Aid for Palestinians (MAP) and 20% will go to RAG charity partners. 🎤 On the 13th evening at 6PM we will also be hosting Dr. Husam Zomlot, Head of the Palestinian Mission to the UK in conversation with LSE Professor Myria Georgiou.

The Unfairness of Fair Machine Learning: Levelling down and strict egalitarianism by default with Brent Mittelstadt

When: 5-6PM, Thursday 16th November

Where: Lecture Theatre B, Department of Computer Science 7 Parks Rd, Oxford OX1 3QG

Abstract: In recent years fairness in machine learning (ML) has emerged as a highly active area of research and development. Most define fairness in simple terms, where fairness means reducing gaps in performance or outcomes between demographic groups while preserving as much of the accuracy of the original system as possible. This oversimplification of equality through fairness measures is troubling. Many current fairness measures suffer from both fairness and performance degradation, or "levelling down," where fairness is achieved by making every group worse off, or by bringing better performing groups down to the level of the worst off. When fairness can only be achieved by making everyone worse off in material or relational terms through injuries of stigma, loss of solidarity, unequal concern, and missed opportunities for substantive equality, something would appear to have gone wrong in translating the vague concept of 'fairness' into practice. In this talk I will examine the causes and prevalence of levelling down across fairML, and explore possible justifications and criticisms based on philosophical and legal theories of equality and distributive justice, as well as equality law jurisprudence. FairML does not currently engage in the type of measurement, reporting, or analysis necessary to justify levelling down in practice. I will propose a first step towards substantive equality in fairML: "levelling up" systems by design through enforcement of minimum acceptable harm thresholds, or "minimum rate constraints," as fairness constraints. I will likewise propose an alternative harms-based framework to counter the oversimplified egalitarian framing currently dominant in the field and push future discussion more towards substantive equality opportunities and away from strict egalitarianism by default.

This weeks screening is a double bill containing Vivienne Dick’s short The Beauty Becomes the Beast and Lou Adler’s Ladies and Gentlemen, the Fabulous Stains. The former depicts a fraught mother and daughter relationship through fractured, chaotic scenes of maturation and womanhood. The latter satirically (though endearingly) depicts a talentless punk band of teenage American girls on tour and probes stardom, authenticity, masculinity, femininity and counterculture. This week’s films are less graphically controversial than subcultural, and the running thematic question seems to concern the cultural contributions of teenage girls to the 20th century, aswell as the limitations in these films’ representations.

Endometriosis matters. And so does your voice.
1 in ten people who menstruate that you know, among your friends, family, or colleagues, are/will suffer from endometriosis. That is as many people as those affected by diabetes in the UK. Help us make endometriosis patients considered! 

Please find linked in our bio an open letter to the Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge, to advocate for the urgent need to fund research on endometriosis within the university.

Endometriosis is an often debilitating life-long condition currently estimated to affect at least 176 million people worldwide - yet we have no known cause nor definitive cure. We urgently need more research on it!

Share this video and sign the letter linked in bio to support endometriosis research. Together, we can make a difference! 🙌 💪🎗️

Queer Film Nights kicks off a season of globetrotting, genre-spanning, feel-good queer cinema with Gregg Araki's hangout classic 'Kaboom', described by one critic as 'Donnie Darko on viagra' and by our programmer as 'your new favourite film'.

Bisexual film student Smith (Thomas Dekker) spends his days hanging out with his partner-in-crime Stella (Haley Bennett), hooking up with fellow student London (Juno Temple), and lusting after his straight roommate Thor (Chris Zylka). Life is sweet. But he's been having strange dreams lately, some guys in animal masks keep showing up, and he's just been passed a note that says he's 'the chosen son'...

Underrated within Araki's filmography, Kaboom was the first recipient of the Cannes Film Festival's 'Queer Palm' award for groundbreaking LGBT cinema, and features music from Placebo, Ladytron, The xx, Interpol, Yeah Yeah Yeahs, and more!

Kaboom will be screened from Blu-ray and will be followed by an informal post-show group discussion.

TW/CW: copious sex and nudity of all genders, flashing lights (non-strobing), manipulative/sexually-coercive behaviour

And that was the last day of the 23rd German Symposium✅

We started off the day with a thought provoking discussion with member of the European Parliament @simonmep on reforming the EU for a stronger Europe. In an intriguing panel discussion, Shakuntala Banerjee and Lars Boering then engaged with us on building bridges in Journalism in the 21st Century. With his expertise in Russian affairs, Jamison Firestone offered us thoughtful explanations on Russia’s true ambitions in Ukraine. Our final talk of the Symposium was held by none other than @jensspahn , who provided us with exceptional and unique insights on government, and how to approach the topic of economic growth. 

We would like to thank all of our speakers and guests for attending and shaping this year’s German Symposium. It was a truly special one!

English singer-songwriter, actress, and author. She rose to prominence as Ginger Spice, as part of the best-selling female group of all time: the Spice Girls. Their slogan "girl power" was most closely associated with Halliwell-Horner and her Union Jack dress from the 1997 Brit Awards also became an enduring symbol. An injury to one is an injury to all! Join the protest Dec 4th Monday 2pm at UCL Print Room Cafe! 

UCL security workers organized in the IWGB union are under attack. The same management that attacks Palestinian solidarity protests with censorship and surveillance are trying to cut the sick pay of security workers at UCL. These workers have been supportive of the movement for Palestinian liberation, including even organizing IWGB contingents on the national Palestine demonstrations. 

We wholeheartedly support their fight for better pay and conditions. We call on all those who support the liberation of the Palestinian people to join us in supporting these workers. Building these links will ultimately strengthen our movement and ensure that our democratic right to protest is protected - not by the fake laws of the reactionary Tory government, but by the workers themselves!

Will we ever escape the male gaze? 
This week we will be discussing all things male gaze. How do we see it in media, art and literature? How does this impact the real world and real life experiences? And what options are there outside of the male gaze? Can we consume or create any art form without taking on the male gaze? What would this look like? And how do we achieve this? 👀👀👀
These are just some of the directions this question could go in, so come along with any and all ideas on the topic, or just to listen in! We can’t wait! 💗
Monday 7pm in the Swire Seminar room (Univ), unlimited alcoholic drinks are £3 for members or £4.50 for non-members, snacks and soft drinks free. See you soon 🙂

We’re thrilled to open this year’s KCLSU elections and invite you to join the 2024/25 KCL Vietsoc committee. As a team dedicated to enriching the Vietnamese community at King’s, we’re looking for passionate individuals eager to foster friendship and cultural exchange.

Key opportunities include organising cultural events, collaborating with other societies and Vietsocs, joining events hosted by SVUK, Vietpro, VFP and the Vietnamese Embassy, and supporting Vietnamese students at King’s. No prior committee experience is needed, just enthusiasm and commitment.

To apply, login to your KCLSU election page and nominate yourself by Monday 19/02. The Vietsoc members will then vote in the election for the new committee in March.

Embrace this chance to make a significant impact in the 2024/25 academic year at King’s College London. During the last 2 years, KCL Vietsoc has grown by more than 100% in terms of memberships, join us in reaching even more members and creating more unforgettable experience for our community!

Whilst the United Kingdom has become an increasingly secularised country, we still have an official state religion. Archbishops and bishops sit in the House of Lords, and the Monarch is the Supreme Governor of the Church of England. Is this right? Is the place of religion within the UK parliamentary system purely a symbolic one, or does it have deeper roots than meets the eye? Should the UK move away from religion within our political system?

Panellists:

The Very Rev. Andrew Tremlett is the current Dean of St Paul’s Cathedral in London, and former Dean of Durham. He founded the Westminster Abbey Institute, which aims to revitalise spiritual values in public life.
Nick Fletcher has been the Member of Parliament for Don Valley since 2019, and is the first Conservative to hold the seat. He is an openly practicing Christian, and described his election win as a miracle performed by God.

Rt. Hon. Baroness Bennett of Manor Castle is a former leader of the Green Party of England and Wales, Baroness Bennett has sat in the House of Lords since 2019. Her 2015 Green Party manifesto advocated for reform of the House of Lords, and a written constitution.

‼️Announcement ‼️We are very excited to introduce our new logo (WOOHOO) !! We have been working on it for the past 2 weeks, choosing from 4 different designs, and here we want to present our final outcome 🥳👏 

💡We chose the light bulb as our main logo, highlighting how many businesses begun with a spark of creative thought. At the same time, using curved brushstrokes, we have created a circular visual effect in the center of our new logo. We want to emphasize the inclusivity and interconnectedness of the creative field. At the same time, they could be seen as people holding on to each other, reflecting one of our aims - providing a platform for students share the interest of exploring opportunities in the creative fields to connect.

Women In Politics and UNSOC are collaborating on an event on Women in Foreign Policy. Sara Sajjad is an LSE alumnus, International Engagement Lead for COP26 and Interviews Coordinator at Women in Foreign Policy. She will be discussing feminist foreign policy, her career in diplomacy, activism concerning climate action, human rights and inclusivity and her views on achieving gender equality in foreign policy. She will be talking about particular case studies, her projects and policies that can be promoted to promote inclusivity.

Join us on Tuesday, February 1st at 5 PM at 32.L and ask her any questions. It will be a hybrid event and will comprise of a 40 minute long talk followed by a 20 minute long question and answer session. 

Register for the event via the link in our bio!

Sara Sajjad currently works for the Unit for International Engagement in the incoming COP26 Presidency team, for the UK Government’s Cabinet Office. The UK hosted the 26th UN climate summit, bringing together parties to accelerate action towards the goals of the Paris Agreement and the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change. She also volunteers for Women in Foreign Policy (WiFP) - an organisation advocating for an intersectional and representative workforce in International Affairs. Sara holds an MSc in Human Rights from The London School of Economics and Political Science and has previously graduated with a First-Class Honours BA in International Relations. During both degrees, she specialized in gender and women’s rights in South Asia. She is interested in championing climate action, human rights, and inclusivity.

Seminar | Cell and Gene Therapy: Promising Science Delivering Value to Patients

🗓️ Date: Wednesday, October 4
🕐 Time: 3:00pm (GMT)
📍 Location: Senate House - UoL, Senate Room
🔗 Registration link: forms.gle/Q8ScN8DBhdzdXB4p6

Join us in our seminar where will talk about Cell and Gene Therapy, hosted by the LSE-SU Health Society.

The seminar will present Dr Miguel Forte, President of the International Society of Gene and Cell Therapy.

We are witnessing a new revolution in Medicine with Cell and Gene Therapy (C&GT) products. These products, with very exciting science and technology, are delivering enormous value to patients with long-term benefit and disease cures. These products are now being approved regulatory wise but are they reaching the patients in need? We will review the status, challenges and opportunities of C&GT products with a forward-looking perspective!

Miguel Forte is a biotech executive, CEO and Co-Founder of Kiji Therapeutics and Entrepreneur in Residence (EiR) with AdBio Partners, Executive Chairman of the Board of StemBond and consulting through mC4Tx to several organizations. Professor at the Lisbon University, he is Board of Directors and Executive Committee member for Alliance for Regenerative Medicine.

The webinar will be moderated by Dr Panos Kanavos, Associate Professor of International Health Policy at the LSE Department of Health Policy.

Our second of many articles to come. Please give them a read and support our correspondents' fantastic work.
Link in Bio
 https://www.uclftr.com/post/leveraging-ai-and-machine-learning-in-finance-the-future-of-sustainable-investment-strategies

"Leveraging AI and Machine Learning in Finance: The Future of Sustainable Investment Strategies" by Miel and Uliana highlights the increasing adoption of AI in fintech, particularly for sustainable investment strategies. It showcases Vistra Corp's success in improving power plant efficiency through AI, resulting in significant cost savings and carbon emission reductions. The article delves into the technicalities of Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs), crucial in optimizing operational efficiency. It underscores AI's potential in guiding investments towards environmentally responsible companies and its growing role in enhancing operational efficiencies in various sectors, aligning with global climate goals and sustainable development initiatives.

Sindhi Culture Ekta Day 2023 Highlights! 🥳✨

Last Saturday, KCL and Sindhi Youth Club came together in cultural harmony to bring to King’s a slice of Sindh! We played games, ate incredible food, indulged in Sindhi art, watched film documentaries, and united everyone from all backgrounds to make this day an absolute success. 🧡

Amid the chilly weather, our shared pot-lunch saw contributors bring in soul-warming food of Sindh. For this, we had the pleasure of Sapna talking about the history and geography of Sindh, her debut cookbook, and the importance of comforting food from home! Give her a follow @sindhi.gusto and check out her website Sindhigusto.com to see more of the incredible things she does! 💚

We want to extend our gratitude to everyone who attended last weekend’s Sindhi Culture Ekta Day ‘23! Shoutout to @sindhigusto for her valuable contributions that brought quintessentially Sindhi food and all-important dialogue to this event! A very big thank you to @thesindhiyouthclub for making this event possible - we are so grateful! We hope every single one of you enjoyed this event, learnt a little bit of something about Sindh, and appeased your appetite for Sindhi cuisine. ✨

We have more so much more events lined up for you next semester, so watch this space to find out more! Thank you to every single one of you who made this event worthwhile - see you all very soon! 🤍

George William Vella KOM KCMG is a Maltese politician who has served as president of Malta since 2019. A member of the Labour Party, he previously served as Deputy Prime Minister of Malta and Foreign Affairs Minister from 1996 to 1998 under Prime Minister Alfred Sant. In 2013, he returned as foreign affairs minister, an office he held until 2017 under Prime Minister Joseph Muscat. Vella is also a qualified medical doctor.

President Vella will be speaking at the Oxford Union on 27th November at 3pm.

President’s welcome HT24!!🌟🌟

Hey everyone! I’m Sophie, a third year Biochemist at Trinity College and I’m honoured to be President of Oxford Women* in Business for Hilary Term 2024!

OxWIB was founded in 2008 with the mission of inspiring the next generation of leaders and breaking stereotypes in the world of business. Since then, OxWIB has grown immensely with a now 45-strong committee. We have been working hard over the winter break to plan our Hilary termcard and help develop resources to build commercial awareness!

This term I am particularly excited for our Inspirational Women’s Series and a new programme in close collaboration with the Saïd Business School, both of which will be launching soon. We’ll be exploring a broad spectrum of sectors including Entrepreneurship, Venture Capital, sustainability, social media and the civil service. We also have events designed to provide actionable advice and insights in the more traditional sectors like finance and consulting. We have our very first Poker Night, the publication of our next edition of the ‘Insight’ Magazine, continuation of our business news digest series and a fantastic President’s Drinks.

The people really do make this society what it is so I’d like to thank my committee for all the hard work that's gone into next term! I encourage you to stay up to date with our events and socials on our social media channels and to get an insight into the OxWIB committee. I wish you a successful Hilary term and am looking forward to meeting you at our events!

Join us in a celebration of South Asia’s rich ethno-linguistic diversity!

Date: Wednesday, 21 February 2024, 6pm - 8pm GMT
Venue: Edward Boyle Auditorium, St Hilda’s College

PERFORM AT THE EVENT:

Committee elections are happening in 2 weeks! Do you want to support the next President in smoothly running the next German Society committee? Then it is time for you to apply to become our next Vice President! 😎🤓 Let’s hear it first from our outgoing Vice President how he looks back on his journey:

How would you describe your role and your responsibility? “Collaborating closely with the President, we ensure the German Society operates effectively and seamlessly. This entails early planning of the term and serving as a liaison within the committee, offering support to all fellow officers in their diverse responsibilities, from problem solving to representing the German Society to guests and external partners.”

What do you look back on with the most joy? What surprised you the most positively? “Amongst the myriad of joys encountered, from seeing the team securing new sponsors to crafting aesthetically pleasing term card layouts and ensuring flawless communication channels, the most profound delight has stemmed from witnessing members eagerly anticipate our events. Furthermore, leading a fantastic committee alongside the President has not only been personally fulfilling but also a very enriching journey of growth, allowing for the contribution of fresh perspectives and ideas into our society’s collective endeavors.”

If you are interested in applying for this position, please send your manifesto (containing not more than 250 words) to Franz Fuchs (secretary@german-society.org) by 18 Feb 7pm. If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to reach out!

Consultant applications are now OPEN!
Application form in the bio!

We are looking for social impact orientated individuals, who want to gain experience in consulting.

As a consultant you will work in teams of 5 on an 8 week project, to then be presented to your client.  You will receive a professional mentor to help guide you through this process.  Prior experience is not necessary, but at least 6 hours of time commitment per week is expected. 

If successful beyond this form, you will be invited to a group case study and competency interview.

For team leaders, additional interview process is expected with a focus on your management and leadership experience.

All applicants must hold a taster or standard membership to be considered.

Join us for our latest talk, with Prof Sir Martyn Poliakoff! As always it is open to anyone (not just members of Trinity) and there will be free snacks and refreshments, so please do come along.
	
This talk will be held in the Pfizer Lecture Theatre, which is in the Department of Chemistry.
	
	Abstract by the speaker:
This lecture describes how I became fascinated in supercritical fluids (SCFs), which are gases such as CO2, compressed until they are nearly as dense as liquids. SCFs display an unusual combination of some of the properties of gases and liquids. I explain how SCFs led me to work in Green Chemistry, developing cleaner, more sustainable ways of making chemicals and materials. I also show how chance played a big role in determining how things developed for me and led me to the interface of chemistry and engineering. I thank all of my students, co-workers, collaborators, technicians and collaborators, particularly Professor Mike George, for all of their help and support. I also thank all of the organisations that have funded my research.

Introducing our second speaker: Oliver, a Senior Lecturer in Nutrition and Exercise Metabolism at King’s College London and deputy programme director for the UG programme in Sport and Exercise Medical Sciences. He is board member of The Nutrition Society and a member of the Royal Society of Edinburgh Young Academy of Scotland. Oliver’s research focus is protein nutrition for maximising muscle adaptation to exercise training. His publications focus on establishing the optimal dose, source and timing of dietary protein for muscle recovery and performance in athletes. Recently, Oliver has delivered invited talks on protein nutrition at international symposiums, including the inaugural FC Barcelona Sports Nutrition in Football conference, The Gatorade Sport Science Institute pre ACSM conference in Boston, and the Royal Society of Medicine winter meeting in London. He has attended the International Sport and Exercise Nutrition Conference for the past 5 years.

Artificial Intelligence is increasingly prevalent in society with seemingly endless capabilities and it has become a player in industries ranging from healthcare to finance. However, questions remain as to what the future holds for AI and on 30th May 2023, hundreds of scientists and notable figures signed an open letter stating that ‘mitigating the risk of extinction from AI should be a global priority. Can we control AI to benefit humanity, or are we, in essence, nurturing our own downfall?

Proposition Guest Speakers:

Max Tegmark is the President of the Future for Life Institute, a Professor of Physics at MIT and a noted cosmologist, having authored over 200 papers.

Jaan Talinn is known for his role co-founding Skype and Kazaa. An early investor of DeepMind, Talinn is also the founder of the Future of Life Institute.

Opposition Guest Speakers:

Yeshimabeit Milner is an American technologist and activist. She is the Founder and Executive Director of Data for Black Lives.

Eric Xing is an AI researcher, President of the world’s first artificial intelligence University, and founder of Petuum inc.

This debate falls within the Oxford Union's Open Period, and can be attended by all students of the University of Oxford and Oxford Brookes.

Debate Dinner Ballot: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSf-5KA_uLr3YtcRofymquRkO4J3_Dtnr22mxPTqq2tMQY2fSA/viewform?usp=sf_link

Emergency Debate Motion: This House believes that the international response to the Israel-Palestine conflict has been insufficient.

[The Global Review Podcast Episode 2023 - 'Revisiting the Castillo dilemma and the underlying implication for Peru']
.
This episode of The Global Review seeks to follow-up on the Castillo Dilemma. We discuss with Professor Cynthia Sanborn, with experience in international relations, on the wide implication for the Peruvian political instability on Latin America Politics and economics.
.
Cynthia A. Sanborn is a Professor of Political Science at the Universidad del Pacífico. She has previously been Vice President for Research and Director of a major think tank at the same university. Dr. Sanborn has written and edited articles and books on issues related to Peruvian and international politics and development, corporate social responsibility, and the extractive industries. Her most recent work has focused on the socio-environmental and political impacts of Chinese investment in Latin America. She is a member of the Working Group on Development and the Environment in the Americas, based at Boston University, and has previously been the William Henry Bloomberg Visiting Professor at Harvard University. Dr. Sanborn received her PhD and MA in Government from Harvard University and her BA in Political Science from the University of Chicago.
.

We are very excited to announce our first event of the year: a talk led by Lucy O'Meara from Art Loss Register. Lucy, the recoveries manager at Art Loss Register, will be sharing her expertise on art crime, due diligence, and provenance checks for art objects and more!

Join us on the 11th of October, at 7pm in UCL Main Campus (Room to be updated on our story and Whatsapp group). Sign up link in bio!

*This is a taster event so no membership required💛

The Art Loss Register (ALR) holds the world’s largest private database of lost, stolen and looted art, antiques and collectibles, currently listing more than 700,000 items. Items are added to this database on behalf of the victims of looting or theft, insurers, police forces and others. Our database is then utilised to offer a due diligence service to clients in the art market who wish to ensure that they are working with items to which no claim will arise. This provides an invaluable risk management tool to our searching clients. Through searching it is also possible to identify stolen items and other claimed works as they move through the art market and to secure their recovery for the claimant.

*Edit: Our new speaker is Olivia Whitting, the Cultural Property Specialist and Client Manager UK and US Auction houses at the Art Loss Register. She is a graduate of the University of St Andrews and SOAS, and has been part of the Art Loss Register Team since 2019.

Medical research overwhelmingly focuses on men. Health issues that only affect AFAB people, like period pain or endometriosis, suffer from a lack of research. Women are excluded from drug trials and ignored by doctors. Can we save women’s healthcare?

Spoiler alert: maybe we can, with the work of amazing campaigns like Oxford Pink Week! Femsoc are so excited to collab with Pink Week for this L&L to raise awareness about breast cancer and support amazing breast cancer charities in Oxford and the UK. 

Come along to the Swire Seminar Room in Univ at 7:00pm on Monday - to chat, or to listen, or to complain about your period pain, PMS and the contraceptive pill! Alcoholic drinks are £3 for members and £4.50 for non-members, and femsoc will donate all drinks proceeds to Pink Week! Free snacks and soft drinks available as usual. We are also encouraging small donations to Pink Week - donors get a fun feminist sticker! 

@oxpinkweek

Exciting news for one of our Playhouse Playmaker alumni, Rhianna Ilube, who has been nominated as one of the ten finalists for the prestigious Susan Smith Blackburn Prize - the "oldest and largest playwriting prize honouring women+ writing for the English-speaking theatre". 

We were delighted to have Rhianna here as a writer on attachment in 2021/22 and are thrilled to see her work being acknowledged.
 
Her nominated play, ‘Samuel Takes a Break... in Male Dungeon No 5 After a Long But Generally Successful Day of Tours’ is playing at The Yard Theatre until Sat 9 Mar.

Uno de los temas que más nos preocupan (y ocupan) son las mujeres mexicanas: que puedan salir tranquilas a la calle; que puedan estudiar lo que quieran; que tengan el trabajo que les guste; que se les pague lo justo por lo que hacen; que la sociedad reconozca y valore su aporte diario; que puedan tomar las decisiones que más les convengan y un largo etcétera. 
Por eso, hoy, varias nos unimos al bloque latino por las calles de Londres para marchar y hablar por todas: las que ya no están, las que están y las que vendrán.

Join us for an inspiring evening of conversation about Social Enterprises featuring Giulia Rosato, CFO at Endelea and Founder of Impact2Bee. Gain insights into shifting to the social enterprise space, fundraising for a social enterprise, and community building as Giulia shares her experiences, challenges, and successes in driving meaningful impact through business.

Date: 22nd February, Thursday
Time: 18:00 - 19:30
Location: Said Business School, East Wing, Seminar Room 13

Following the Fireside Chat, stick around for networking drinks where you can mingle with like-minded individuals, share ideas, and forge new connections in the realm of social innovation. Don’t miss this opportunity to engage with a leader in the field and join a community passionate about making a difference!

Like all the most disruptive innovations, Artificial Intelligence is likely to significantly change our relationship with strategic sectors of our economy and improve our relationship with the social and economic realities we are all part of.

But, like all the opportunities, Artificial Intelligence also raises important questions. Will we be able to truly make un effective use of it? And how might these new technologies impact on the labour market and the socio-economic organisation to which we are accustomed?

Join us this Thursday for a hybrid Q&A with Professor David Chalmers on the nature of consciousness and philosophical progress. This discussion will focus on two of Professor Chalmers’ articles, 'Debunking Argument for Illusionism about Consciousness' (2020) and 'Why Isn’t There More Progress in Philosophy?' (2017), as well as a recent lecture he gave entitled 'Could a Large Language Model be Conscious?' (2023).

For this hybrid Q&A, Professor Chalmers will be attending remotely via Zoom. During the first half-hour, the PhilSoc Co-President will ask Professor Chalmers a few questions that delve into the core ideas and insights of these two articles and lecture. The remaining half-hour will be dedicated to audience questions.

IMPORTANT: We will not be admitting people at the door who have not booked tickets online, via the link in our bio. If you're a member, check your email for the event's promo-code. If you're a member and have not received a promo-code, please email David.Conway@pmb.ox.ac.uk. For those wanting to become members, you can follow the other link in our bio (Oxford-philsoc.org/membership).

When: W6 Thursday 22 Feb, 6:30-7:30 pm
Where: Lecture Room, Radcliffe Humanities

Dr. Marcel Weil, head of group for 'Sustainable Energy Technologies' at KIT, will be holding the next event co-hosted with the Cambridge Energy Society. 

Batteries are considered as a key technology for the mobility and energy system transformation, to meet the ambitious CO2 (and sustainability) goals of the United Nations COP 21 conference in Paris. Present Lithium Ion Batteries (LIBs) owns manifold problems and challenges from a sustainability perspective.
Thus, future post lithium battery systems (Post-LIBs) have to overwhelm present challenges and outperform present LIBs from a sustainability perspective. The presentation will show, how to assess the environmental sustainability performance of present and future batteries along the life cycle, and how the results can be used to advice technology developers and other stakeholders.

You can also join us online! Zoom link will be posted closer to the date

For more information DM us!

(Belated) Day 16 of '24 Reasons to Join Wheelchair Basketball in the New Year'!

You can use world-class accessible facilities!

Our normal venue, Oxford's Acer Nethercott Sports Hall, is a state-of-the-art court with a backlit LED floor which changes court markings for different sports. There are also fully accessible toilets, changing rooms, showers and a water fountain. There are 3 blue badge parking spaces, and a whole carpark for visitor parking.

**December/January: Unfortunately we will not be in the Acer til next Febuary as the LED floor is made of glass, and smashed (Oxford 🧠) - so we are in the other Iffley Road sports court, which is slightly less accessible, but we can enter with a ramp. Message us to arrange to meet in the reception so we can guide you to the temporary venue...

At the weekend our freshers travelled to C*mbridge for their first taste of Varsity. Well done to all those who competed! The match report by Will Parry (Men’s Captain) is below:
On a crisp November morning at Iffley Road, the nervous but excited freshers made the journey to Cambridge to compete at the 2023 Fresher’s Varsity Match. Travelling with two trophies on board the coach, and the strong will to retain them, there was a big day ahead for the freshers. We made the journey to Wilberforce Road, took the traditional pre-varsity photos, and our freshers donned OUAC vests for the first time.
 
There was a strong start with success in many of the earlier events, with wins in both 400 hurdles and hammer, followed by a very strong performance from Sofia Stefani leading to an 800m victory on the women’s team. Laura Anene then started her very successful day with long jump, followed soon after by a triple jump win and personal best (in November!). Grace Cardwell heroicly decided to add the 100m hurdles to her already extensive list of events to gain some crucial points for the women’s team, with Quinn Pidgeon following in her footsteps. He volunteered to attempt the high hurdles with minimal practice, but still performed very impressively in the race. The sprinters were against very stiff competition, however helped display an excellent demonstration of composure, remaining relaxed, controlled, and fast in very cold conditions.

Throughout the day the throwers had been grouped at the far side of the track, churning out result after result with some exceptional throws mixed in there. Cayen Wang and Willem Jump were each asked to do a majority of the throws, with Wang winning both the javelin, hammer and shot put, whilst Jump managed a substantial win in the hammer. Perhaps the most notable feat of the day was a 52.45m javelin throw from Damon Zuber, who’d spent most of the day stuck on trains after delays on his travels to Wilberforce Road.

Despite their best efforts, the men didn’t quite manage to pip the tabs to the post, however, the women’s team retained the trophy after a draw, a very substantial feat for an away fixture, leaving lots to be excited for!

Salam everyone. LSESUMENA is organising tomorrow a bake sale fundraiser for those affected by the earthquake in the north-west of Syria.    
   
As many of you know, Syria has been under US and European sanctions for decades, making relief efforts even harder to reach the country's borders in a time of crisis like this. Even with the recently announced exemption, Syrians on the ground are continuing to suffer and endure the wait of receiving humanitarian assistance as the situation becomes progressively worse.    
   
Luckily, there are charity and aid initiatives that are working on the ground to do what they can, and so all proceedings will be split across a number of them.    
   
Please do come and support if present on campus; your support and contribution in any way is needed!!

We’re grateful to have had another successful year at KCL Bhangra! 

We kicked off this year with a performance at Fresher’s fair, where we had the opportunity to showcase the art of bhangra to the wider King’s community. 
We followed Fresher’s week with our annual fresher’s classes at the end of September, which received an incredible turnout 🤩 
(Make sure to look out for our Fresher’s events this year, coming soon! 👀) 

Throughout October and November we ran our beginner level weekly classes, and our Diwali show team trained diligently for their performance at @kcldiwalishow at the start of December 🔥

For the rest of December, January and February, our competitive team worked hard rehearsing for @official_tbs The Bhangra Showdown competition, which led to KCL Bhangra’s THIRD TBS WIN!🥇 🏆 

We followed our triumph at TBS with two open classes - both a music and a live class! Thank you to everyone who attended these classes, and make sure you check out the full class videos on our feed 🥳📽️

We rounded off the year with some extra gig performances - a big thank you to our partners who invite us to perform year after year. 

For everybody who has supported KCL Bhangra over this year, we are incredibly thankful 🤍 we have some big plans for the upcoming academic year, so make sure you’re following this page to stay updated and get involved!

RIMSKY-KORSAKOV - ANTAR

Inspiration for Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov’s symphonic suite Antar was derived from an Arabian legend in which Antar, a recluse living in the desert, kills a large bird to save a gazelle. Falling asleep, he dreams that the gazelle was the Queen of Palmyra, who, as a reward, grants him three joys: vengeance, power, and love. The first movement of Rimsky-Korsakov’s Suite depicts this narrative whilst the subsequent three explores each of the three joys respectively.

In early November, our event welcomed two representatives from the UK Parliament, aiming to enlighten students about the intricacies of the parliamentary system. This event catered not only to students studying politics and policy, seeking context for their studies and firsthand insights into their subjects in real life, but also served as an eye-opener for those who might not have been familiar with the workings of Parliament.

The session began with an interactive lecture, followed by a lively Kahoot quiz that tested the participants' newfound knowledge and sparked healthy competition. This was followed by board games and group discussions, allowing attendees to network, exchange ideas, and explore parliamentary concepts in a more relaxed setting. The highlight was the presence of two representatives from the UK Parliament, whose firsthand accounts enriched the discussion, providing valuable insights and great advice for gaining a parliamentary career! 

Image Descriptions: 
1️⃣ The audience of 55 attendees gathered for an engaging hour-and-a-half event.
2️⃣ The banner for the event, titled Engaging and Influencing Parliament with the LSESU 93% Club sets the tone for an impactful session.
3️⃣ Illustrating the diverse range of topics covered during the lecture, from understanding Parliament and the Government to exploring opportunities within the UK Parliament.
4️⃣ A dynamic moment during the event, showcasing participants actively engaging in discussions, asking questions, and sharing their thoughts, fostering a collaborative and interactive learning environment.
5️⃣ A display of snacks was provided to maintain high energy levels and enhance the overall experience of the event.
6️⃣ A behind-the-scenes glimpse into the preparation before the event.

Students for Global Health Cambridge is excited to host a talk featuring speakers Prof. Ashley Moffett and Dr. Charlotte Patient! In the talk, Dr. patient will cover the challenges of obstetrics in Uganda in a tertiary referral hospital, and the multitude of fundamental differences encountered such as in the presentation of clinical symptoms, course of disease and treatment responses. Prof. Moffett will go into the scientific projects she has done in collaboration with Dr. Annette Nakimuli, a researcher at Makere University in Kampala.

About the speakers

Prof. Moffett trained as a physician at Cambridge and London. She then entered the field of histopathology, and worked as a pathologist at the Rosie Maternity Hospital. In the late 1980s Prof. Moffett became interested in pre-eclampsia and the role of the immune system in its pathogenesis. She returned to Cambridge to investigate basic science of placentation in the Department of Pathology, where she currently works.

Dr. Patient is an Obstetrician currently working in Cambridge. She has a particular interest in maternal medical disease during pregnancy. Dr. Patient is also involved in postgraduate medical education and has recently been appointed to a post promoting Global Health amongst trainees in the East of England.

Oxford students will elect the next six Sabbatical Officers for 2024-2025, alongside voluntary positions and the RAG charities. Any student can put themselves forward for nomination for any of the roles in the election!

The six Sabbatical Officer positions available in the 2024 elections are:
•	President
•	Vice-President Activities and Community
•	Vice-President Liberation and Equality
•	Vice-President Postgraduate Education and Access
•	Vice-President Undergraduate Education and Access
•	Vice-President Welfare

There are also voluntary roles up for election for students who are passionate about student democracy at Oxford:
•	NUS Delegate x9
•	Student Trustee x3

You can find all of the information you need, including role descriptions, election rules and more at the link in our bio.

For week 4, we are very excited to announce that we will be hosting Dame Carol Propper, where she will be delivering a talk titled 

“Is competition in healthcare good for your health?”

Dame Carol Propper is the President of the Royal Economics Society and a member of President Macron's expert commission on major economic challenges. Propper was appointed Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) in 2010 for her work in the social sciences, and Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire (DBE) in the 2021 New Year Honours for services to economic policy and public health. Her work focuses on the economics behind health care reform, and she has served as an Economic Advisor to the National Health Service.

Please join us for what is sure to be an amazing talk, and don't worry, there will be plenty of time for questions and discussions!

This month Oxford Pride celebrates and honours the extensive queer history of our city and the resilience and diversity of our LGBTQIA+ community. 
 
Our city, renowned for its intellectual prowess and cultural significance, has been a witness to the struggles and triumphs of the LGBTQIA+ community for centuries. From the shadows of secrecy to the forefront of advocacy, countless individuals have left an indelible mark on the city’s history. While some might be familiar with notable figures like Oscar Wilde at Magdalen College or Evelyn Waugh’s connection to Hertford College, the comprehensive range of queer experiences in Oxford has only recently been acknowledged and appreciated.
 
As we reflect on the past and celebrate the present, let us continue to stand together, united in the pursuit of a future where love, respect, and understanding prevail within the heart of our beloved city.
.
.
.
.
.

Removing invasive species and how to watch them sustainably!

Grafham water is in within a Site of Special Specific Interest environmental designation. This means protection is of national conservation interest because of the support of wildlife. Stay within designated areas, avoid anchoring, dispose of waste, avoid approaching wildlife and use eco-friendly products.

Moreover, there is a risk of killer shrimp at Grafham, this always make sure to CCD your dinghy!

Take good care of the wildlife and environment so that we can enjoy it the longest.
#greenblueunichallenge @roosterkit @the_green_blue

In this time of transition we look back at some last year’s special moments. 

During the 2022/2023 end of year dinner, former head coach Dave Mace handed out the yearly awards. Freya Leyland received the ‘character award’, for ‘always being cheerful and smiling, whatever the circumstances’, even after a loss or at any given rainy early morning training. Roberto Lacourt received the ‘best boxer award’ after winning BUCS and enriching the club with his years of experience and talent. Mili was awarded for her contributions to the club and ‘saving Varsity’ through months long negotiations for a new Varsity agreement. 

The same evening two more awards were awarded. George Garner received the ‘best boxer of the evening’ award which was funded by alumni Joseph Kotrie Monson and awarded by David Butler, bursar at Vincent’s club and alumni member. George received the award for his outstanding performance at this year’s Varsity match. 

David Seiferth was the first time receiver of the Robert Nairac award, an exceptional award for the ‘boxer with the most heart’. David received the award for his unwavering support to the club and the fact that he has never missed a training, and ‘is always ready to box’, or as Dave put it: ‘I wish I had 9 of him’.

🔸 We are excited to announce that Member of the German Bundestag Jens Spahn will join us as a speaker at the German Symposium 2024. 

@jensspahn is a key figure in German politics and a member of the Christian Democratic Union (@cdu). Spahn has been a pivotal member of the German Bundestag since 2002.He has been actively involved with the CDU since 1997, chairing the CDU district association of Borken since 2005 and serving on the federal board of the CDU since December 2012.Spahn’s political career includes serving as the Parliamentary State Secretary at the Federal Ministry of Finance from 2015 to March 2018. He then took on a significant role as the Federal Minister of Health, contributing to the Merkel IV cabinet from March 2018 to 2021. Additionally, he has been a member of the CDU’s executive committee since 2014 and served as one of the deputy leaders of the CDU from January 2021 to January 2022.

— 
🔸 We are excited to announce that Lawyer and member of the New York Bar Jeremy Firestone will join us as a speaker at the German Symposium 2024. 

Jamison Firestone is a businessman lawyer who has managed law firms for over twenty five years. He was a member of the Board of Directors of the American Chamber of Commerce in Russia for six years and lived in Russia for eighteen years. He is a member of the New York Bar.
Since the controversial death of his former employee Sergei Magnitsky, Mr. Firestone has dedicated his life to bringing justice to this case. As the Co-Founder of the Global Magnitsky Justice Campaign, he now specialises in sanctions, asset recovery, defense from extradition, in Russian law, and defending clients from Russian criminal and civil actions both in Russia and abroad.

✨️MT23 Dance Team Auditions✨️

If you're interested in joining group dance covers, performing at local events, and participating in national competitions, you might be interested in auditioning for our dance team 🌟 You don't need to have prior dance experience - we're looking for enthusiasm, energy, and ability to learn in addition to technique, and many of our dance team members had very little experience before auditioning! 

For the audition, please prepare two choreos out of the four from the MT23 Audition video on our YouTube channel - you can also find it at the link in our bio! You may also prepare an optional third choreo from a song of your choice, as long as it is within 30-60 seconds and is either a kpop choreo, a choreo performed by a kpop artist, or a choreo from a Korean dance studio (e.g. 1MILLION). 

Auditions will be held in person at the Magdalen College squash courts on 21-22 October from *2-6pm* each day! You can book an audition slot at the Calendly link in our bio, but if none of the options work for you, please reach out and we'll find an alternative time. 

Just let us know if you have any questions about the process. We're so excited to see your auditions - good luck! 🍀

Join the Edgar Wind society’s exclusive talk and book signing with artist Tam Joseph. 

Tam Joseph was born in Dominica in 1947, and moved to London with his family when he was 8 years old. He studied at Central School of Art and briefly at the Slade School of Fine Art. He lives and works as an artist in London. His work has been exhibited internationally and is represented in many public collections including the Arts Council Collection, Tate Modern, and the V&A. 

Tam’s paintings reflect on his own history and the history of injustices faced by African Caribbean people in Britain. Other works draw inspiration from diverse sources including cinema, music, and sport, as well as the natural world, and the history of painting itself.

THE MAN, THE MYTH, THE LEGEND - on the SEVENTH day of Christmas my true love gave to me: ANDREW HANNAFORD!!!

Clearly a hit with the ladies (Martha...), 'Daddy garg' Andrew returns this year to treat us once again to his plummy bass - the corridors are once again ringing with sonorous discussions of Oxford coffee houses or rare French wine vintages.

So Andrew, why did you join the gargs?
"As an enthusiastic young bass, the decision to dive into the intricate harmonies and improvisational spirit of jazz a cappella wasn't just a musical choice; it was a personal quest for self-expression, collaboration, and the sheer joy of..." ect. ect. ect.

If you were a jazz musician, who would you be and why?
"Frank Sinatra - surely understandable" [Steady on]

Favourite thing about Gargs?
"Ben Gilchrist"

Member of the gargs most likely to survive an apocalypse?
"Ben Gilchrist"

Tell me a joke!
"Wife asked if I'd seen the dog bowl, I said I didn't know he could!" [this is deeply representative of Andrew's humour]

If you were a scat syllable, what would you be and why?
"Bah - you don't know when it will hit you" 

Favourite Gaga song?
"Chromatica II"

On Monday, we are delighted to host television presenter Clive Tyldesley, who has been involved in broadcasting and the media for over four decades, being the soundtrack to some of the biggest football games during that time. From FA Cup Finals to World Cups, his work has brought him around the world and led to a wealth of experience. Clive will talk about the growing trend of discourse and debate being stifled, and how he wants to challenge younger generations to save it, and utilise mass media for good rather than bad. 🎥📺

On Tuesday at 5pm, we will be welcoming Jonny Wilkinson CBE, an English former rugby union player. He played for Newcastle Falcons and Toulon and represented England and the British & Irish Lions. Widely acknowledged to be one of the best rugby union players in history, he scored the winning drop goal in the 2003 Rugby World Cup Final. In total, he won 91 caps for England. He was inducted into the World Rugby Hall of Fame in 2016, two years after retiring. 🏉
