Get ready for the grand final of our Meet-the-Team Thursday extravaganza! Today’s spotlight shines on the committee members who ensure the smooth running of the club behind the scenes by sharing their sheer endless wisdom on all things rowing. Hold onto your oars, because their top race memories are coming your way!

Anna: Secretary
“Winning my first-ever sculling race with David at Henley T&V this summer despite being super nervous!”

Gavin: Social Secretary
“Summer 8s 2022, I got M2 blades in my first summer 8s! The tension on the final day was unreal.”

Grant: Safety Advisor & Kit Officer
“My favourite race in WCBC was the M4+ finals at Oxford City Regatta. We unfortunately came 2nd in the final but had a great time blasting backstreet boys on our way back to the boathouse!”

Galen: Treasurer
“Bumping Jesus in the 2020 Lents, then stealing their flag.”

Giovanni: Equipment Officer
“One of my fondest racing memories is when I definitely - didn't - fall into the river with my bike while bankriding.”

Alex: Development Officer
“Summer VIII’s 2023. We lost… a lot. But it was such a positive crew and we gave it everything we had. Honoured to have fought hard and gotten spoons alongside such a strong, supportive group of ladies.”

Aimee: Captain of Coxes & Regatta Secretary 
“Apart from bumps racing which is just so unique there is no comparison, my favourite races are probably Milton Keynes regatta for the happy atmosphere and good weather, the novice regatta because it's a continual source of entertaining stories and fond memories to look back on, and shocking as it may seem Quintin head. Quintin was the first race I ever did and if you can survive being on the Tideway in January then you know you can do anything.”

Dominik: Webmaster & Regatta Secretary  “My favourite race so far was Day 2 of Torpids 2022 — we were chasing Balliol for the second day in a row, but they again managed to bump coming out of the gut. We were able to stay together and continued to chase down Pembroke, getting the overbump just in front of the boathouse.”

Join us for an exciting event featuring Yuval Atsmon, Senior Partner at McKinsey, taking place on Friday, 17th of November at 18:00 at Bush House - Lecture Theatre 3. 

Having worked at McKinsey for over 20 years, Yuval Atsmon has notable consulting experience. After graduating from Tel Aviv University with a Bachelors in Law, and later an MBA at Harvard Business School, Yuval started at McKinsey as a Consultant. At McKinsey, he quickly ascended roles, spending 6 years in Shanghai where he led the Strategy Practice for the Greater China, helping international companies to navigate China's rapidly changing economic landscape. After a series of promotions, he is now a senior partner focused on serving TMT and Consumer clients. Alongside this, he is a prolific author, frequently contributing to the McKinsey quarterly and Harvard Business Review online.

William Carlos Williams (1883-1963) was a physician/litterateur who famously composed his eponymous work 'Paterson' - a poem of 6 books ( just about!)- on his home town in New Jersey, America.

Taking inspiration from his writing process, we will be holding an informal walking and writing workshop this Saturday. We will meet outside The Mill Pub (near Scudamores), walk towards Grantchester- pausing to take inspiration- and finish at a cafe to reflect, write up our ideas, and share some readings from our own work or from 'Paterson'.

Day 3 of posting about our advisory projects for the year! Please note these are just examples; once you are accepted to a team, you will receive more in-depth information. 

We have one project with St Andrews this year and it will be a market analysis. This is a skill everyone in the consulting/finance industry will need to know. Your team will study the market for mental health educational services. The focus will be on demand, pricing and positioning. By the end of the project we hope you will have recommendations for St Andrews.

Key concepts this project will include are: creating a market analysis, mental health services and proposing recommendations.

St Andrew's Healthcare is a charity providing specialist mental healthcare. They provide education and training to healthcare staff and students, share learning and insights, campaign to reduce the stigma around mental health and much more.

Read more about how St Andrew works here: 
https://www.stah.org/

On the 27th of October, Cambridge Climate Justice rallied to call for Fossil Free Research, bringing together students, staff and community members alike. Over the past five years, the University of Cambridge accepted an average of £3m of fossil fuel funding each year. 

As early as 1977, the fossil fuel industry knew about climate change and funded biased research to hide it. Now, the same companies fund research for greenwashing or promoting false solutions to the very problem they created and keep fuelling.

Students and academics will not compromise with academic freedom. Join us to defend research integrity, and get fossil fuels off campus.

⭐️ONLY 3 HOURS LEFT to apply for Raise Oxford's 2023/24 committee, the student charitable society that has raised almost £50,000 in the last three years!⭐️

We have extended our deadline so if you missed out last term, now's your chance to apply‼️

APPLICATION DEADLINE: Sunday September 17th @ midnight.
Link in bio for the application form and information on available roles.

WHAT IS RAISE OXFORD?
Raise Oxford is a charitable movement encouraging students to adopt a positive approach towards deliberate, effective giving. Student donations made through Raise are doubled by our sponsors, so 200% of every donation goes to charity. Our charity of choice is the Against Malaria Foundation, chosen for its rating as one of the most effective charities. At the end of the year, we come together to celebrate our collective impact at our annual Summer Party.

There are plenty of roles available, whether you are interested in fundraising, sponsorship, events or publicity! All are encouraged to apply regardless of prior experience.

You can find more information on what we do at our website (link in bio), or feel free to send us a DM or email us at raiseoxford@gmail.com.

South Asian Week Day 2 - Are we still living in a colonised world?

Sir Roger Penrose is a mathematical physicist and Emeritus Rouse Ball Professor of Mathematics at the University of Oxford. In 1988 he received the Wolf Prize in Physics, which he shared with Stephen Hawking for the Penrose–Hawking singularity theorems. In 2020, He received the Nobel Prize in Physics “for the discovery that black hole formation is a robust prediction of the general theory of relativity”. 

In this talk, he will introduce his challenging views on the collapse of the wave function, linkage with consciousness, and offer his personal insights into the philosophy of quantum mechanics itself.

Kindly note that this event is expected to be oversubscribed, and is part of a large-scale event. Owing to this significant nature, we will be allocating tickets on a first-come first-serve basis and charge a small fee to help cover venue costs, so be sure to sign up quick to avoid disappointment if you are interested!

Time: 15:30 PM
Venue: Andrew Wiles Building, Mathematical Institute
Price: £9 for general entry, £7 for Oxford students

12 Days of Crisis: Day 7
*Raising awareness for the Rohingya refugee crisis*

On 25 August 2017, a massive exodus of 745,000 Rohingya refugees began to flee Myanmar. Now, in 2020, nearly one million people remain stranded in vast refugee camps.

Description: Hairdresser Ali Johar, 30, cuts his 2-year-old daughter Humera’s hair in the Rohingya refugee camp. Families like Ali’s live completely within the refugee camp, with no foreseeable opportunity to establish their lives in a more settled or safe environment.

Photographer: Patrick Rohr
Date: 15th May 2018

«С обывательской точки зрения мир, в котором Россия нападает на Украину, палестинцы убивают евреев, а евреи проводят тотальную “зачистку” палестинских территорий, хуситы блокируют Красное море, а китайцы грозят заблокировать Жёлтое, ужасен и необычен. С исторической точки зрения, однако, это и есть нормальный мир, ровно такой, каким он был тысячи лет до этого. А вот последние приблизительно 40 лет, когда интенсивность глобального насилия в мире была относительно невысокой, а количество войн ограниченным, являлись как раз выдающимся периодом мировой истории, возникшим вследствие совпадения уникальных обстоятельств».

In collaboration with the Telles Foundation, UCL is pleased to offer a scholarship that removes financial barriers for talented Brazilian students to access a world-class education at UCL’s Department of Electronic and Electrical Engineering (EEE). The UCL Telles Scholarship is funded through a gift from the Telles Foundation - an international charity that provides transformational opportunities to low-income people in Brazil by improving their access to education.

Route:
1-year Undergraduate Preparatory Certificate (UPC) - starting September 2024:
- Designed specifically to prepare international students for a UCL undergraduate degree.
- This intensive one-year foundation course is taught on our central London campus.
- Experienced UCL teachers will support you to develop your academic skills, English and subject knowledge so you can progress to your degree programme.

3-year Electronic and Electrical Engineering (EEE) BEng:
- Electronic and electrical engineers invent and create the technology that typifies today’s high-tech society, from devices and systems that monitor our health and well-being, to global data networks, driverless cars and renewable energy.
- The EEE BEng gives you a broad education in the engineering, mathematics, physics and computer science underpinning these technologies, whilst at the same time giving you the skills needed to put your theoretical understanding into practice.

UCL is now accepting applications for September 2024 entry. Check whether you’re eligible for the Telles Scholarship and the UPC and find out how to apply, with application guidance and frequently asked questions (link in our bio).

Join us for Qube Research & Technologies Workshop Event on Monday 30th October, 5-6pm in MR2, CMS Core!

Xavier Brokmann, Quantitative Research Director will give the following talk: ‘Overfitting: perspectives from quantitative finance’

Abstract:
In-sample biases in systematic investing. Whether it's to discover new signals, build optimised portfolios or manage risk, systematic investing heavily relies on a familiar work horse: running back-tests on historical data.
In this talk, we will show that despite its many strengths, this approach also exposes systematic investing to various in-sample biases.
We will illustrate the magnitude of the challenge these biases represent in quantitative finance, and also discuss various approaches to mitigate them when designing systematic trading strategies.

There will be pizza and networking in the Central Core afterwards!

Get ready for next week where Karen Underwood, Rebecca Woolington, and Nicole Clewer will be leading a roundtable discussion on Redefining Success with Nonlinear Career Paths✨
 
Karen Underwood – X-Press Legal Services
Karen Underwood currently owns and manages two businesses providing reports and data for conveyancers and property solicitors across the Thames Valley and Somerset. She started X-Press Legal Services as a franchise in 2007 and has constantly grown and expanded since then. 
However, this was not her planned career, and the journey has been an unusual one. Karen originally trained and worked as a professional dancer before giving that up to join her family firm of funeral directors. Here she qualified as the first female funeral director in Oxfordshire, gained business management qualifications and was the managing partner by the time the business was sold in 2000.
 
Rebecca Woolington – HR Central 
Rebecca Woolington is an accomplished qualified HR Professional with over 30 years of HR and Recruitment experience. Rebecca is the founder of HRCentral Limited, an independent, industry agnostic HR Consultancy offering HR support and talent acquisition on an hourly basis for SME across the UK.

Nicole Clewer – Clewer Communications 
Nicole Clewer is the founder of Clewer Communications and lover of all things social media. Nicole has worked in the social media industry for almost 5 years and is lucky enough to experience working on both sides of the grind, initially working as a social media ambassador for a renowned fitness brand, and working with brands such as Sure Deodorant and River Island. She now manages social media accounts for many successful businesses.

UCL Punjabi Society wishes you all a Happy Diwali and Bandi Chhor Divas ! 🪔🎇

Diwali and Bandi Chor divas are celebrated on the same day every year. They are two different festivals where Diwali is celebrated by Hindus and Bandi Chhor Divas by Sikhs. 🪯🕉️

Bandi Chhor divas means “Prisoner Liberation Day ''. On this Day Sikhs celebrate the day the sixth Guru, Guru Hargobind ji was released from Gwalior Fort in 1619. Guru Hargobind Sahib Ji had been imprisoned by the Mughal emperor Jahangir for refusing to bow down to him . Once he had  returned to the holy city of Amritsar the whole city was lit up with diyas and lamps in their happiness of seeing him back. Some rituals Sikhs follow on this day are Visiting gurdwaras, listening to kirtan, lighting diyas and setting off fireworks. Sikhs also use Bandi Chhor Divas as an opportunity to reflect on the teachings of Guru Hargobind Sahib Ji. Guru Hargobind Sahib Ji taught Sikhs to stand up for what is right and to fight for justice. 

In Hinduism Diwali is celebrated usually during the Hindu lunisolar months of Ashvin (according to the amanta tradition) and Kartika—between around mid-September and mid-November. Diwali  symbolises the spiritual "victory of light over darkness, good over evil, and knowledge over ignorance. In southern India, Diwali celebrates the victory of Lord Krishna's destruction of the demon Naraka who is said to have imprisoned women and tormented his subjects. In northern India, Diwali honours the triumphant return of Lord Rama, his wife Sita, and brother Lakshmana, from a 14-year exile in the forest. Celebrations include :  Diya lighting, puja (worship and prayer), havan (fire offering), vrat (fasting), dāna (charity), melā (fairs/shows), home cleansing and decoration, fireworks, gifts, and partaking in a feast and sweets.

TO ALL SLADE STUDENTS - NOTES FROM YESTERDAY'S UCL COMPENSATION MEETING!

Notes from the open meeting yesterday with Asserson Law Offices (who are the people putting together the case for student compensation due to strikes and the pandemic).
- Firstly, just to explain the basics of it, essentially they are aiming to refund between a third to a half of student fees. This is open to anyone who has studied at ucl between 2017 and 2021, as earlier years were still affected by strikes.
- Secondly, it’s really important that we get people to join the student group claim, which you can sign up for here: https://studentgroupclaim.co.uk/ The more students that join, the more money we can ask for. At the moment there are already over 2,000 students signed up, but Asserson is hoping and predicting between 5,000 – 10,000. There is no fee for joining, and there won’t be any financial cost to students throughout the case (all of it is covered by a litigation funder). 
- Thirdly, and really importantly, you cannot receive compensation unless you are signed up to the claim!!!! Please make sure you go through both stages of signing up, including putting in course info. 
- Fourthly, Asserson has said they will work directly with UCL to make sure students aren’t penalised for joining, which is very unlikely in the first place.
- Fifthly, out of any compensation given by UCL, we are guaranteed a 70% minimum (with 30% maximum going to Asserson and the litigation funder).
- Sixthly and lastly, the court process will be a long one (they estimate a year and a half) but after the initial sign up, there should be nothing more they need us to do on our end.
PLEASE SPREAD THE WORD AROUND, especially if you are part of other UCL societies – the more students join, the greater the compensation is likely to be
(if you have any worries or questions, the email to contact is francesca.caller@asserson.co.uk )

12 Days of Crisis: Day 10
*Raising awareness for the Rohingya refugee crisis*

On 25 August 2017, a massive exodus of 745,000 Rohingya refugees began to flee Myanmar. Now, in 2020, nearly one million people remain stranded in vast refugee camps.

Description: A young boy is examined by a doctor in MSF's clinic next to Nayapara refugee camp. The child's mother, Mumtaz, arrived in Bangladesh in October 2017 to escape the latest wave of violence in Rakhine State, Myanmar. His father died trying to reach Bangladesh.

Photographer: Anna Surinyach
Date: 22nd January 2018

Nathan Law is an activist and politician from Hong Kong. He came to prominence in 2014 as a student leader of the large-scale ‘Umbrella Movement’ protests. The founder of the pro-democracy party Demosisto, Law was elected to the Legislative Council of Hong Kong in 2016. At 23, he was the youngest legislator in the territory’s history – and was disqualified by the government from taking his seat. Following the introduction of the highly controversial ‘National Security Law’ in 2020, Law fled to London, where he now lives in political exile.

We are keen to hear from the activist on the 22nd of November at 5pm.

✉️ Fun Facts about Louboutin

For Christian Louboutin, every woman is a work of art, a goddess meant to be celebrated, a life source of limitless power that ought to be unleashed. At the age of 16, he began an internship at the famed Folies Bergère, where the self-taught shoemaker began dressing the dancers’ feet with his designs.

Soon after, the world became his stage. Christian Louboutin’s sketches caught the eyes of various renowned designers to whom he lent his talents while learning the more technical aspects of his craft. In 1991, the designer embarked on a new adventure that would come to define his legacy: the inauguration of his first Parisian boutique.
And the rest, chéris, is red soled history.

MEET THE COMMITTEE! 
Our next Women’s Vice-Captain is Jess, who is starting her second year in History and Politics.
Born to network, forced to row, Jess may have been groomed by her college parents into her rowing obsession (although she denies this), but her fierce stroking and fast splits are here to stay. Her proximity to the cox’s microphone provides the whole boat with constant comedic relief. Let’s hope it doesn’t always reach other boats on the river, or they might start questioning our sanity. 
Bring a coat when Jess is in the boat - beware of her splashing. She’s the reason that the club has Thames Water on speed dial to return the river level back to normal after she’s been rowing. Water belongs in the river, not the boat Jessica! 
As a horse girl, the river has been a new challenge that Jess has stepped up to, stroking the W2 crew to success in both the 2023 Torpids and Summer VIIIs campaigns. 
For Becks’ (her sculling partner) sake, and for anyone Jess might cox, let’s hope that Jess steers better on the river than on Mario Kart, or indeed than on the road. 
We can’t wait for the women’s side to benefit from Jess’ continual energy and vitality.

❗Our first MT newsletter is out❗

China is planning a 'Giant New Leap' - but who wins the semiconductor war?
(Article by Lucas Appleton)

Amidst a backdrop of a global microchip shortage, a new battleground is forming between East and West. Xi Jinping’s vision of a “Giant Leap” for China by 2035, amounting to the doubling of average GDP per capita, is ambitious. Access to high-quality semiconductors is key to achieving this. However, the imposition of ‘chip’ export regulations imposed by the USA to China over technology, manufacturing equipment as well as technical know-how and personnel will severely hinder this.
 
China already is a manufacturer of lower-quality chips. Building a new high-tech facility would cost an estimated $20 billion, with a risk that the technology would be obsolete upon construction. China’s interest in another producer of high-quality chip production is now clearer – Taiwan.

Hey guys, Mr RUMS FC here. As I’m sure you are aware, a certain (see slide 3) has introduced me to a world of fame within RUMS. This something I don’t take lightly, and therefore have developed 3 key principles in my life. LOYALTY, IDENTITY, RELIABILITY

Loyalty- pretty self explanatory really. I strive for loyalty in all walks of life. I’m hearing a few rumours about me joining UCL, but I’m here to put this bed once and for all. Cut me open and I bleed blue and yellow. (But please Ben Horsewell start me on Wednesday).

Identity- if you haven’t heard me mention it, I am a northerner. My whole personality is based on the fact I am from 2 hours north of London so expect steak bakes and sausage roll nights instead of horrifically awful curry nights this year! Also did you know I scored the winner at varsity last year? Oh sorry, forgot I already said it.

Reliability- Can always rely on me to make a bouncers night more difficult than it is to pronounce joes second name. Dunno what they’re complaining about all I did was call them a charva, must’ve been something to do w my accent. If u didn’t already know I scored in varsity wait no I mean I’m from up North, sorry about that . It’s not like me to mention varsity unnecessarily. Anyway ,another thing you can always rely on me is to always make it home on time. Even if It means sleeping in a church courtyard and turning up shoeless at 6 am.

To round it off here’s just a quick few of my likes and dislikes

Likes: calling simplicity 5 times during a sportsnight, Pete BOC, purple, head injuries, tuna 

Dislikes: MNF, returning home from a night out, Andras’ breath

Look forward to this year lads…and remember…. Keep it 🍋

Presenting Day 2 of our 2024 Italian Symposium “A New Italy in a New Europe” - 28th February to the 2nd of March🇮🇹🌍

⚡️Panel 1: “Beyond Earth: The Experience of an Italian Astronaut” with Paolo Nespoli at 16:30, LSE Lecture Theatre, Centre Building, LSE

Major Paolo Angelo Nespoli is an Italian astronaut and engineer of the European Space Agency (ESA). In 2007, he first traveled into space aboard the Space Shuttle Discovery as a mission specialist of STS-120. In December 2010 he again traveled into space aboard the Soyuz TMA-20 spacecraft as an Expedition 26/27 flight engineer. Nespoli’s third spaceflight was on board Soyuz MS-05, which launched in July 2017 for Expedition 52/53.

⚡️Panel 2: “The Future of the EU Single Market” with Enrico Letta at 18:15, Sheikh Zayed Theatre, Cheng Kin Ku Building, LSE.

Enrico Letta is an Italian politician who served as Prime Minister of Italy from April 2013 to February 2014, leading a grand coalition of centre-left and centre-right parties. He was the leader of the Democratic Party (PD) from March 2021 to March 2023. In 2023, the European Council appointed Enrico Letta as EU rapporteur on the future of the Single Market.

🎟Tickets for the Symposium will be available on Monday 19th February. Places are limited so book your place in advance! The Symposium will be live streamed on our Youtube channel for those that cannot attend 📸.

In this week's continental conversations, we will trace Edward Said's account of the development of the key features of Orientalism to better understand how Orientalism feeds into how we talk, view, and act towards the East.

Regarded as one of the leading public intellectuals of his time, literary and cultural critic Edward Said was steeped in the Western literary canon and was hailed as the father of postcolonial studies. Both an Arab Christian and an American citizen, Said's book Orientalism reflects upon how the Western-Eastern relationship is informed and upheld through purportedly objective academic discourse and skewed cultural representations, spanning the pre-colonial to post-colonial.

This cultural discourse, Orientalism, has mediated how the West views and interacts with the East, especially the Middle East, serving as an implicit justification for colonial ambitions; equally, this discourse has inserted itself onto how the East views itself. Furthermore, Said takes issue with the very ontological distinction made between "the East" and "the West," arguing instead that this distinction is chiefly epistemological, artificially constituted through cultural discourse.

When: W4 Thurs Feb 8th, 7-8pm
Where: Mary Hyde Eccles Room, Pembroke College
This event is open to all!

The Logical Route to the Turing Machine: What inspired Alan Turing to Invent Computer Science?

When: 5-6PM, Thursday 26th October

Where: Tony Hoare Room, Robert Hooke Building, Parks Road, Oxford OX1 3PR

Turing’s 1936 paper was a landmark in the history of computer science - but how exactly did it come about? In this talk, we will discuss the philosophical origins of the Turing machine and the paradox that inspired it.

Speaker Bio:

Peter Millican originally studied Mathematics at Oxford, but graduated in Philosophy and Theology before moving into postgraduate study in Philosophy (also at Oxford). After a brief spell lecturing in Philosophy of Religion at Glasgow, from 1985 until 2005 he lectured in Computer Science and Philosophy at Leeds University, where much of his work was devoted to building interdisciplinary links. In 2005 he became Gilbert Ryle Fellow at Hertford College, then Reader in Early Modern Philosophy in 2007, and Professor of Philosophy in 2010.

I thoroughly enjoyed this meeting, under the relaxing social enjoyment of UFC 294 together, of two of the most demanding and rigorous clubs UCL offers.

It's my hope our two clubs will become even more closely aligned as we recognise the exceptional value that comes with camaraderie between fellow Scholar Warriors such as we are.

Thank you all for coming!

In May 2027, NASA is launching its Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope, which will look at the gaps between elongated groups of stars to help astronomers reveal dark matter! 

This will be done using globular clusters: sometimes stars can be stripped away from their globular clusters, causing ribbon-like streams of mostly gas and some stars. The gaps between these can possibly be caused by dark matter – there are a few streams in the Milky Way but astronomers want to look at globular cluster streams in other galaxies.

Roman will take a large snapshot of the Andromeda galaxy that isn't possible with any other telescope, and astronomers will be able to study globular cluster streams there. Dark matter is expected to interact with them, so the telescope team is developing a theoretical framework to determine where these streams originated and whether they'll be observable by the Roman. 

The second image is simulated, showing how much the Roman could capture in a single shot, and the image of the moon is provided for scale. 

For more information, check the link: https://www.nasa.gov/missions/roman-space-telescope/nasas-roman-to-search-for-signs-of-dark-matter-clumps/

1st image credit: NASA, Joseph Olmsted (STScI)

2nd image credit: NASA, NASA-GSFC, ASU, Robert Gendler DSS; Simulation: NASA, STScI, Benjamin F. Williams (UWashington)

Hello everyone, I hope you’re having a good start to week 7! We’re Oxford Entrepreneurs (@oxentrepreneurs) and we’re taking over the @oxunistudents account this week 🥳 

We’re the biggest entrepreneurship society in the UK with several thousand members 🚀 Society members are current undergraduate and postgraduate students at the @oxford_uni, MBAs, EMBAs, active alumni, faculty members and industry experts. 
Every term we organise various events such as panel discussions, pitch competitions, networking sessions, startup career fairs and workshops. 
Membership is free, so make sure to check out our events, no matter what your degree or experience is! 🙂

Ecosia is a search engine that uses profit from internet searches to plant trees! It is a free browser extension with 100% of the profits going to planet action and 80% of these to planting trees.
🌱 Including the obvious benefit of using Ecosia, it also allows you to track your own impact on ecosystems and communities, performs exactly the same as most popular search engines and their solar panels provide enough for searches! 🌱

Ecosia uploads monthly financial report on their website and they have a blog section where they provide articles and videos about varied environmental subjects.
With a lower carbon impact than most other search engines, this is a great way to help the planet while searching and surfing on the web! It is even possible to make it your main search engine and do private searches as well. So add Ecosia to your Chrome today for free and start planting trees!🌳

If you want to learn more go visit their website at www.ecosia.org and info.ecosia.org

Dear all, as promised we are back today with a different concept from Sustainability Sunday. We are proud to introduce to you the Sunday Green Challenges! The aim of these challenges is to each week, encourage you guys to take a specific action that would help reduce your carbon footprint or promote sustainable living. The challenges will be easy to implement and tailored to the current season or upcoming events. A hashtag will be associated with each challenge, so you can post a story of yourself completing it every week (don't forget to tag us) ;) This will allow you to share your experiences and progress with our community!!

We will start right away with our first challenge: this coming week, your challenge will be to cycle to a place you normally go to by car or public transports at least once! Use the #KCLcycling and tag us on your story to share how you did:) Good luck !

OPMS is proud to host Dr. Ron Zimmerman on the 22nd of November 🗣️‼️ 

Dr. Ronald is a fellow from the University of Cambridge 🌉 who founded the Public Health Genetics Unit, and is the Chairman of the PHG Foundation, an independent charity focusing on the impact of genomics and molecular science on health. He has enjoyed a distinguished career in medicine, public health and policy, and is the pioneer of public health genomics in the UK.

Join us at the MBI Al Jaber Auditorium, Corpus Christi College, for his talk on Personalised Medicine: It’s Public Health Genomics Antecedents 💊🩺..
